Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Background:

Since its inception in 2008, Foodhub has been a one-stop point for POS solutions for Takeaways and Restaurants across the United Kingdom. Through the years, we have grown manifold, and are now operating in five countries: UK, Egypt, Australia, New Zealand and India. We now have a workforce of 700+ and a plan to expand the team to 1000+ employees in a very near future.

Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. [3 marks]¶

In [ ]:

Using the rating_df would be better as df1 includes the 'not given category'

Dropping the 'not given' rating and changing the datatype to numeric in rating_df
'''


# Convert 'rating' column to numeric with cleaned_df (without 'not given' rating)
rating_df.loc[:, 'rating'] = pd.to_numeric(rating_df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Calculate count of ratings and average rating per restaurant
rating_count_per_rest = rating_df.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].count()
average_rating_per_rest = rating_df.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].mean()

# Filter for <50 rating count and avg rating <4
eligible_rest = (rating_count_per_rest > 50) & (average_rating_per_rest > 4)
promotional_offer_rest = eligible_rest[eligible_rest].index

# Print
print("Restaurants fulfilling the criteria for the promotional offer:", promotional_offer_rest)

# Charging percent to filtered order amount
charging_percent_25 = 0.25  # 25% for orders greater than $20
charging_percent_15 = 0.15  # 15% for orders greater than $5

# Calculate revenue from each order
total_revenue = 0
for cost in df1['cost_of_the_order']:
    if cost > 20:
        total_revenue += (cost - 20) * charging_percent_25
    elif cost > 5:
        total_revenue += (cost - 5) * charging_percent_15

# Net revenue generated by the company across all orders
print("Total revenue generated by the company across all orders is:", total_revenue)

  • Most revenue is generated from orders between \$5 to \$20

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Key focus of the analysis is to answer

  • How to enhance customer experience?

Conclusions:¶

The Dataset given about foodhub has been analysed to understand the trends and patterns of how to enhance the customer service experience. With the help of descriptive analysis and visualisations, some insights have been drawn as below:

Key insight

1) Cuisine Diversity: The dataset encompasses a wide variety of cuisines, comprising a total of 14 types offered by 178 unique restaurants.

2) Popular Cuisines: American and Japanese cuisines dominate customer preferences, collectively constituting 55% of cuisine choices.

3) Top Restaurants: Notable establishments such as Shake Shack, The Meatball Shop, and Blue Ribbon Sushi emerge as the most popular among customers.

4) Performance Analysis: Shake Shack emerges as the highest-performing restaurant, boasting the highest total orders and revenue generation, with an impressive \$3,500, surpassing the second-ranking restaurant by 1.5 times.

5) Rating Trends: Customer ratings exhibit limited significance, with a majority of customers refraining from leaving ratings, as evidenced by the highest count of 746 ratings marked as 'not given'.

6) Weekend Ordering Surge: Customers display a clear preference for weekend orders, with order counts doubling compared to weekdays, accompanied by a notable increase in average spending by \$4.

7) Cuisine Preference: American cuisine remains the preferred choice for customers both during weekdays and weekends.

8) Consistent Delivery Times: Across various days and cuisine types, restaurant food preparation and delivery times demonstrate consistency, with no discernible data suggesting delivery time as a significant issue for customers.

9) Weekend Spending: Customers exhibit a propensity to spend more on weekends, contributing to a higher revenue stream, particularly within the \$5 to \$20 order range, which accounts for 15% of total revenue.

10) Order Distribution: The majority of orders, accounting for 71%, fall below the \$20 threshold, indicating a preference for moderately priced items among customers.

Recommendations:¶

These insights provide valuable guidance for refining strategies aimed at optimizing customer satisfaction, promotional activities, and operational efficiency.

1) Cuisine Focus: Prioritize American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese cuisines based on customer preferences and expenditure patterns.

2) Weekend Promotions: Launch promotional events specifically targeting weekends to capitalize on higher customer spending and order frequency, resulting in an average increase of \$4 per order and a doubled order count compared to weekdays.

3) Targeted Promotions: Offer promotional deals on orders priced between \$5 to \$20, focusing on customers from high-traffic restaurants:

Top Restaurants:

  • Shake Shack
  • The Meatball Shop
  • Blue Ribbon Sushi
  • Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken

4) Delivery Efficiency: Despite only 10% of orders taking longer than 60 minutes from preparation to delivery, prioritize ongoing efforts to maintain efficient delivery times. While data doesn't suggest a significant impact of total delivery time on customer ratings, maintaining prompt service remains crucial for customer satisfaction.

5) Review Encouragement: Recognize that 38% of customers do not leave ratings. Implement strategies to encourage customers to review restaurants, enhancing the experience for both new and existing customers by providing valuable insights when selecting restaurants.

How to improve this analysis to gain deeper insight and actions for enhancing customer experience?¶

Given the dataset's limitations, particularly concerning customer information, a more comprehensive understanding of the Foodhub user experience can be achieved by incorporating the following data points:

1) Customer Status:

  • Distinguish between new and existing customers to tailor promotions and understand user behavior over time.

2) Account Creation Dates:

  • Capture the dates when users created their accounts to analyze user engagement and retention trends.

3) Order Dates:

  • Record timestamps of orders to discern patterns in ordering behavior, such as peak times and seasonal fluctuations.

4) Days of the Week:

  • Analyze ordering frequency and spending habits on individual days of the week to optimize promotional strategies and resource allocation.

5) Restaurant Locations:

  • Collect location data for restaurants, including city, region, and area, to assess geographical preferences and target promotions effectively.

6) Demographic Information:

  • Gather demographic data such as gender and age to segment users and personalize marketing efforts.

7) Reviews:

  • Capture both positive and negative reviews to gauge user satisfaction levels and identify areas for improvement in service and restaurant selection.
